<subSubSection id="C30175E2FFBCFFAFC6A453E5FEF2FD50" box="[151,383,726,753]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BA42669FFBCFFAFC6A453E5FEF2FD50" blockId="8.[151,598,690,753]" box="[151,383,726,753]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">
(
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFBCFFAFC6AC53E5FE92FD51" box="[159,287,726,753]" captionStart="FIGURES 5" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1487,1511]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1461]" captionTargetId="figure-19@9.[151,1436,179,1461]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 5A–F. Pseudacteon inticlinatus sp. nov., female. A. head, anterior view; B. wing, dorsal view; C. fore tarsus, posterior view; D. mid tibia, posterior view; E. hind femur, anterior view; F. ovipositor, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559542/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Figs. 5A–F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFBCFFAFC71953E5FEFAFD50" box="[298,375,726,752]" captionStart="FIGURES 24" captionStartId="33.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[203,1388,188,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-19@33.[190,1398,179,1917]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURES 24A–J. Tergite VI and sternite VI of females.A–B. P. quadrisetalis Liu et Cai; C–D. P. trapeziformis Zhang et Liu; E–F. P. inticlinatus sp. nov.; G–H. P. setipalpatus Disney et Michailovskaya; I–J. P. reticulatus sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559613" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559613/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">24E–F</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30175E2FFBCFFAFC6A4522DFE05F9D4" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BA42669FFBCFFAFC6A4522DFE66FC69" blockId="8.[151,1437,798,1977]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">
<emphasis id="B96FFA7BFFBCFFAFC6A4522DFE9FFC98" bold="true" box="[151,274,798,824]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Female. Apical seta shorter than maximum width of palpus; fore tarsomere 5 longer than fore tarsomere 1; setal palisade 3/4 length of mid tibia; setulae below basal half of hind femur shorter than those of anteroventral row of outer half; tergite VI reduced to a narrow anterior strip in middle but each lateral quarter with 3 long setulae; sternite VI not divided, with 4–5 very long setae each side; dorsum of oviscape with 8 short setulae each side, of which five are short and stout.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA42669FFBCFFAFC6F452E1FB82FB64" blockId="8.[151,1437,798,1977]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">
<emphasis id="B96FFA7BFFBCFFAFC6F452E1FEA8FC4C" bold="true" box="[199,293,978,1004]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Female.</emphasis>
Body length 
<quantity id="4CE38B8CFFBCFFAFC7F352E1FDA5FC4D" box="[448,552,978,1005]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.04" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" unit="mm" value="1.04">1.04 mm</quantity>
. Frons (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFBCFFAFC4B052E1FD56FC4D" box="[643,731,978,1005]" captionStart="FIGURES 5" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1487,1511]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1461]" captionTargetId="figure-19@9.[151,1436,179,1461]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 5A–F. Pseudacteon inticlinatus sp. nov., female. A. head, anterior view; B. wing, dorsal view; C. fore tarsus, posterior view; D. mid tibia, posterior view; E. hind femur, anterior view; F. ovipositor, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559542/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
) brown, with 36–40 setulae. Supra-antennal setae as strong as adjacent frontal setae, lower pair being closer together and a little higher than lower fronto-orbital setae. Lower interfrontal seta directly under lower fronto-orbital seta. Lower fronto-orbital setae near to eye margin and a little lower on frons than upper supra-antennal setae. Second row of frontal setae a little concave, with upper interfrontal setae clearly further apart than either is from an upper fronto-orbital seta. Flagellomere 1 brown and subglobose. Palpus pale brown, with short setae, apical one as long as adjacent setulae and shorter than maximum width of palpus. Labrum pale brown. Labella pale brown and with long and curved setulae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA42669FFBCFFAFC6FD55FDFB5FFA60" blockId="8.[151,1437,798,1977]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">
Thorax brown. Scutellum with two pairs of setae, posterior twice length of anterior. Legs yellowish brown to brown, hind femora being darkest. Ratios of lengths of fore tarsomeres about 0.84: 0.74: 0.69: 0.65: 1, with all five bearing a setal palisade (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFBCFFAFC7D55425FDCCFA91" box="[486,577,1302,1329]" captionStart="FIGURES 5" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1487,1511]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1461]" captionTargetId="figure-19@9.[151,1436,179,1461]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 5A–F. Pseudacteon inticlinatus sp. nov., female. A. head, anterior view; B. wing, dorsal view; C. fore tarsus, posterior view; D. mid tibia, posterior view; E. hind femur, anterior view; F. ovipositor, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559542/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
). Setal palisade extends more than 3/4 (0.72) length of mid tibia (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFBCFFAFC3075425FA02FA91" box="[1332,1423,1302,1329]" captionStart="FIGURES 5" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1487,1511]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1461]" captionTargetId="figure-19@9.[151,1436,179,1461]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 5A–F. Pseudacteon inticlinatus sp. nov., female. A. head, anterior view; B. wing, dorsal view; C. fore tarsus, posterior view; D. mid tibia, posterior view; E. hind femur, anterior view; F. ovipositor, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559542/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Fig. 5D</figureCitation>
). Setulae below basal half of hind femur longer than adjacent setulae of anterior face, but clearly shorter and weaker than those of anteroventral row of outer half (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFBCFFAFC4B8546DFD6DFAD9" box="[651,736,1374,1401]" captionStart="FIGURES 5" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1487,1511]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1461]" captionTargetId="figure-19@9.[151,1436,179,1461]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 5A–F. Pseudacteon inticlinatus sp. nov., female. A. head, anterior view; B. wing, dorsal view; C. fore tarsus, posterior view; D. mid tibia, posterior view; E. hind femur, anterior view; F. ovipositor, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559542/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Fig. 5E</figureCitation>
). Wing (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFBCFFAFC50E546DFC1FFAD9" box="[829,914,1374,1401]" captionStart="FIGURES 5" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1487,1511]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1461]" captionTargetId="figure-19@9.[151,1436,179,1461]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 5A–F. Pseudacteon inticlinatus sp. nov., female. A. head, anterior view; B. wing, dorsal view; C. fore tarsus, posterior view; D. mid tibia, posterior view; E. hind femur, anterior view; F. ovipositor, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559542/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
) length 
<quantity id="4CE38B8CFFBCFFAFC5DF546DFBDDFAD9" box="[1004,1104,1374,1401]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.08" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" unit="mm" value="1.08">1.08 mm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity id="4CE38B8CFFBCFFAFC293546DFA88FAD9" box="[1184,1285,1374,1401]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" unit="mm" value="0.55">0.55 mm</quantity>
, width/length 0.51. Costal index 0.40. Costal ratios 1.55: 1. Costal cilia 
<quantity id="4CE38B8CFFBCFFAFC52A54B1FC5AFA3D" box="[793,983,1410,1437]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.45" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.4" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" unit="mm" value="0.0245" valueMax="0.025" valueMin="0.024">
<geoCoordinate id="EE2F40AEFFBCFFAFC52A54B1FCD5FA3D" box="[793,856,1410,1437]" degrees="0.024" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" precision="55" value="0.024">0.024</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate id="EE2F40AEFFBCFFAFC56A54B1FC28FA3D" box="[857,933,1410,1437]" degrees="0.025" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="8" pageNumber="209" precision="55" value="-0.025">–0.025</geoCoordinate>
mm
</quantity>
long. Costa with 16 dorsal setulae. Alula with 2 setae. Veins brown, thin veins being paler. Membrane brownish gray. Haltere pale yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA42669FFBCFFAFC6FD54F9FCD1F9F1" blockId="8.[151,1437,798,1977]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">
Abdominal tergites brown and tergites 1–5 with sparse minute setulae only. Tergite VI (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFBCFFAFC28154F9FA9BFA44" box="[1202,1302,1482,1508]" captionStart="FIGURES 24" captionStartId="33.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[203,1388,188,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-19@33.[190,1398,179,1917]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURES 24A–J. Tergite VI and sternite VI of females.A–B. P. quadrisetalis Liu et Cai; C–D. P. trapeziformis Zhang et Liu; E–F. P. inticlinatus sp. nov.; G–H. P. setipalpatus Disney et Michailovskaya; I–J. P. reticulatus sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559613" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559613/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Fig. 24E</figureCitation>
) reduced to a narrow anterior strip in middle but each lateral quarter bears 3 long setulae at rear margin. Sternite VI (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFBCFFAFC30054DDFA19F9A8" box="[1331,1428,1518,1544]" captionStart="FIGURES 24" captionStartId="33.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[203,1388,188,1898]" captionTargetId="figure-19@33.[190,1398,179,1917]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURES 24A–J. Tergite VI and sternite VI of females.A–B. P. quadrisetalis Liu et Cai; C–D. P. trapeziformis Zhang et Liu; E–F. P. inticlinatus sp. nov.; G–H. P. setipalpatus Disney et Michailovskaya; I–J. P. reticulatus sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559613" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559613/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Fig. 24F</figureCitation>
) with 4–5 long setae each side. Oviscape arched. The dorsum of the oviscape with about 8 short and stout setulae each side, of which five near apex are short and stout (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFBCFFAFC4CA5705FCC2F9F1" box="[761,847,1590,1617]" captionStart="FIGURES 5" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1487,1511]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,179,1461]" captionTargetId="figure-19@9.[151,1436,179,1461]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 5A–F. Pseudacteon inticlinatus sp. nov., female. A. head, anterior view; B. wing, dorsal view; C. fore tarsus, posterior view; D. mid tibia, posterior view; E. hind femur, anterior view; F. ovipositor, dorsal view. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559542" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559542/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Fig. 5F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA42669FFBCFFAFC6F45769FE05F9D4" blockId="8.[151,1437,798,1977]" box="[199,392,1626,1653]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">
<emphasis id="B96FFA7BFFBCFFAFC6F45769FE89F9D4" bold="true" box="[199,260,1626,1652]" pageId="8" pageNumber="209">Male</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
